Overview
This project centralises sales and reference data from all 11 MeridianMart branches into a single PostgreSQL warehouse. The pipeline follows a simple ELT pattern:

Extract raw rows from 11 transactional Google Sheets + 4 reference sheets

Load them unmodified into the raw schema in PostgreSQL

Transform everything inside Postgres using SQL (staging → marts → reporting)

The goal is to replace 11 disconnected spreadsheets with one validated, queryable source of truth for store, regional, and product performance.

Data Sources
Transactional Data (11 Sheets)
Each store has its own Google Form for logging sales. Every line item becomes a row in that store’s response sheet.

Captured fields include:

Product sold

Quantity

Payment method

Receipt number

Optional customer phone number

Timestamp

Staff name (free text)

Reference Data (4 Sheets)
Centrally maintained Google Sheets:

Product Master (65 products, 15 categories, GHS pricing, manager audit trail)

Staff Master (90 staff, roles, store assignment)

Managers Master (25 managers, hierarchy, store/region assignment)

Stores Master (11 branches, city, region grouping)

Pipeline Architecture
Extraction Layer (Python)
A Python script (Google Sheets API + SQLAlchemy/psycopg2) performs:

Authentication

Pulling all 15 sheets

Loading each sheet as‑is into its matching raw.* table

No joins, no transformations, no cleaning at this stage

Daily automation via cron

Database Layers
Layer	Purpose
raw	Direct dumps of Google Sheets (untouched)
staging	Constraints, validation, referential checks
marts	Star schema: fact + dimensions
reporting	Aggregated tables for BI consumption


Core Tables (Data Dictionary)
fact_transactions
Central fact table built after validation and reference resolution.

Primary Key: transaction_key (surrogate)
Foreign Keys:

store_id → dim_stores

staff_id → dim_staff

product_id → dim_products

date_key → dim_date

Key Columns

receipt_no — cashier-entered basket ID

sale_timestamp — raw Form timestamp

quantity — units purchased

unit_price_ghs — resolved via product join

total_amount_ghs — computed

payment_method — Cash / Card / Transfer

customer_phone — optional, used to derive customers

dim_products
Product catalogue with pricing and manager attribution.

Primary Key: product_id  
Foreign Key: updated_by → dim_managers

Columns include:

product_name

category

unit_price_ghs

last_updated

updated_by

dim_staff
Full staff roster used to resolve raw Staff Name entries.

Primary Key: staff_id  
Foreign Key: store_id → dim_stores

Columns include:

full_name

role

store_id

phone_number

employment_status

dim_managers
Management hierarchy (Store, Assistant, Regional).

Primary Key: manager_id  
Foreign Key: reports_to → dim_managers (self‑reference)

Columns include:

full_name

role

store_id or region

email

date_appointed

dim_stores
Reference table for all 11 branches.

Primary Key: store_id

Columns include:

city

region (Southern, Middle Belt, Northern)

dim_customers
Derived dimension created by deduplicating phone numbers.

Primary Key: customer_id (surrogate)

Columns include:

phone_number

first_seen_date

total_visits

Entity Relationships (Star Schema)
fact_transactions → dim_stores (N:1)

fact_transactions → dim_staff (N:1)

fact_transactions → dim_products (N:1)

fact_transactions → dim_date (N:1)

dim_staff → dim_stores (N:1)

dim_managers → dim_stores (N:1 for Store/Assistant)

dim_managers → dim_managers (self-referencing hierarchy)

dim_products → dim_managers (price updates)

Data Flow Summary
Cashiers submit Google Forms → Sheets accumulate raw rows

Python script extracts all sheets daily

Raw tables receive unmodified data

Staging tables apply constraints and validation

SQL transformations build fact + dimensions

Reporting schema produces daily/weekly/monthly summaries

Data Integrity
Enforced via Postgres:
CHECK constraints (e.g., quantity 1–20)

Foreign keys (product, staff, store must exist)

NOT NULL rules

Additional validation:
audit.validation_log records issues such as:

Duplicate receipt numbers
Slightly mismatched product/staff names across stores

Project Objectives
1. Centralise All 11 Store Sources
Daily extraction of all store sheets + 4 reference sheets into Postgres.

2. Enforce Data Quality at the Database Layer
Use constraints + validation scripts to catch structural and referential issues.

3. Build a Full Star Schema in SQL
Create fact and dimension tables directly inside Postgres.

4. Resolve Price & Category via Join
Ensure pricing comes from the Product Master, not the sales form.

5. Build Cross‑Branch Reporting
Daily sales, regional rollups, top products, payment mix.

6. Automate the Daily Run
Cron‑scheduled Python runner orchestrates extraction → validation → transformation.

Why This Approach Works
Lean stack (Python + SQL)

No vendor lock‑in

Full control over validation and transformation

Scales cleanly as stores or sheets increase

Replaces manual spreadsheet reconciliation with a single warehouse


MeridianMarkt/
├── .env                       # Database connection parameters & user credentials
├── raw_schema.sql             # Database DDL defining the raw schema staging tables
├── extract_transactions.py     # Component extracting and unioning the 11 store sheets
├── extract_references.py       # Component truncating and reloading the 4 reference sheets
├── extract.log                # Ingestion pipeline execution audit trail log
└── README.md                  # Project overview and system documentation